SINGLE VARIABLE ANALYSIS

#To Do: inspect all of the variable distributions.

#The variables are Age, Cabin (converted to Cabin_deck in column 15), Embarked, Fare, Name, Parch (parents or children of passenger), Passenger ID (3 digit number), Pclass (1,2,3), Sex (male/female), SibSp (Siblings or Spouses), Survived (0=no, 1= yes), Ticket (various letters/numbers, all different, not useful), Title (Master (young boy), Miss, Mr, Mrs, Dr, Rev), Family Size (the sum of SibSp + Parch, a created column), Cabin_deck (A,B,C,D,E,F,G,U (unknown) where all C123, C586, etc are grouped into deck C, etc). The single variable assessment of each variable is below in the order given above.

COLUMN 1 “AGE”, USING BOXPLOT BECAUSE BARCHART ISN’T FEASIBLE FOR SO MANY DIFFERENT AGES, NEED STATISTICS
##SINGLE VARIABLE ANALYSIS OF ** AGE ** LOOKS LIKE YOUNGER PEOPLE SURVIVED A BIT BETTER, BUT NOT STRONG TREND
titanic$Survived <- as.factor(titanic$Survived)
ggplot(data=titanic, mapping = aes(x = Survived, y = Age)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
      coord_flip()

COLUMN 2 “CABIN”, there are all different codes like E46, C85, so sorting by just the letter if we can and create a 15th column called “Cabin_deck” to sort by.

#A’s 15, B’s 46, C’s 58, D’s 32, E’s 31, F’s 12, G’s 3, NA’s 686, so can only do percentage survived

### SINGLE VARIABLE ANALYSIS OF CABIN, CONVERTED TO LETTER ONLY MEANING DECK OF SHIP #####
### FIRST FILTER TITANIC TO CREATE titanic_no_cabin_na SINCE ONLY 204-ish HAVE CABIN NAMES
titanic_no_cabin_na <- filter(titanic, !is.na(Cabin))
## NOW YOU HAVE A 204X14 FILE CALLED titanic_no_cabin_na so you can see which deck saved the most lives

## NOW add a 15th variable to titanic_no_cabin_na called Cabin_deck to compare survival on Decks A,B,C,D,E,F,G
titanic_no_cabin_na <- titanic_no_cabin_na %>% 
  mutate(Cabin_deck = ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^A"), "A", 
                            ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^B"), "B",
                                   ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^C"), "C",     
                                          ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^D"), "D",
                                                 ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^E"), "E",
                                                        ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^F"), "F",
                                                               ifelse(str_detect(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin, "^G"), "G",
                                                                      "U"))))))))
### now the titanic_no_cabin_na has 15 columns. 
titanic_cabin <-select(titanic_no_cabin_na, Cabin_deck)

## geom_bar uses the count of the number of cases, geom_col uses the values in the data.  This geom_bar correctly plots
## A=15, B=46, C=58, D=32, E=31, F=12, G=4 and U=1
ggplot(data=titanic_cabin) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Cabin_deck, fill = 'count of cabins'))

titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin_deck <- as.factor(titanic_no_cabin_na$Cabin_deck)
titanic_no_cabin_na$Survived <- as.factor(titanic_no_cabin_na$Survived)


ggplot(data=titanic_no_cabin_na) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Cabin_deck, fill = Survived),
           position = "fill")

### we see that we got close to 75% survival on decks B, D, E, which aren't necessarily the most populated decks
### The survival rate drops from D/E to F to G, as you go lower on the ship, the decks that flooded first.
COLUMN 3: “EMBARKED” : C=Cherbourg, Q=Queenstown, S= Southampton - no missing values
## first just a basic bar graph to see what % survived from each port of embarkation
## will look at this in the multi-variable analysis to see men/women vs. port of embarkation
titanic$Pclass <- as.factor(titanic$Pclass)
titanic$Survived <- as.factor(titanic$Survived)

ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Embarked, fill = 'count of embark locations'))

ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Embarked, fill = Survived),
           position = "fill")

## We see that overall, port C had the best survival rate, and port S had the most people (>600) to save, compared to 
## port C, which had more like 180 people to save, so there could be a trade-off there.  ALSO WE COULD LOOK TO SEE IF PORT
## C HAD MORE WOMEN AND/OR HIGH-FARE (RICH) PEOPLE.

ggplot(data=titanic) +
   geom_bar(mapping = aes(x=Embarked, fill = Pclass),
            position = "fill")

## Yes, this examination of Embarkation by Pclass shows that probably the reason Port C had more Survived is that they were 
## proportionately Pclass = 1 passengers.  And probably the reason Port S had fewer Survived is that they were mostly Pclass 3
## passengers.  However, Port Q was the highest proportion of Pclass 3 passengers, yet its survival rate beat Port S, but that
## could also be because there were only <100 Port Q passengers, which makes it easier to save them than > 600 Port S 
## passengers.  So this variable DOES SPEAK TO THE IMPORTANCE OF Pclass IN WHO SURVIVED!

COLUMN 4: “FARE” (num) 10 entries with zero fare, mean ~ 13, median ~14, max 512, so plot 10-11 bars of 50 width each

## well I don't like the graph above because it has too many distinct fares, so I want to create categories
## The categories are < $1, $10-20, $20-30, $30-40, $40-50, $50-100, $100-200, $200-300, and > $300 is called $500)     COMPLETE
titanic <- read_xlsx('titanic_partial.xlsx')
titanic$Fare <- as.numeric(titanic$Fare)
titanic <- titanic %>% 
  mutate(Fare_class = if_else(Fare < 1, 1,
                         if_else(Fare <= 10, 10,
                                   if_else(Fare <= 20, 20,
                                        if_else(Fare <= 30, 30,
                                                 if_else(Fare <= 40, 40,
                                                        if_else(Fare <= 50, 50,
                                                               if_else(Fare <= 100, 100,
                                                                    if_else(Fare <= 200, 200,
                                                                            if_else(Fare <= 300, 300, 500))))))))))
titanic$Fare_class <- as.factor(titanic$Fare_class)  
titanic$Survived <- as.factor(titanic$Survived)

ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Fare_class, fill = Survived), 
           position = "fill")

## *** FAMILY_SIZE *** reinitialize (note this will result in no Col 15, but we don't need Cabin_deck for this section  COMPLETE
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(stringr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
titanic <- read_xlsx('titanic_partial.xlsx')
titanic$Title <- as.factor(titanic$Title)
titanic$Survived <- as.factor(titanic$Survived)
### When we plot it just by Parch, note that if Parch =0 (no parent or children traveling with them) then their probability
### of surviving looked worse, which makes sense that they would save families first.  But it could be that those single people 
### were men traveling alone, which died more
ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Parch, fill = Survived))

### This single plot of SibSp (siblings and spouses) had pretty much the same result that people traveling solo fared worse, 
### but again it could be mostly men traveling solo, and it's really gender that is the affect.  Obviously statistically, each 
### time you add a person, there's a probability it's a woman - there were 36% women and 64% men on the Titanic (assuming 
### that Rev and Dr were men, so if you add Parch or SibSp, with each add there's a 35% it's a woman)
ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = SibSp, fill = Survived))

### Ok, third graph is the sum of SibSp and Parch, which is Family_Size (column 14).  This sums up this group of variables
### well, showing if someone is traveling alone, they are far more likely not to survive, and if they travel in a moderate sized ### group, their odds get better, but in the really large groups, it might not have been possible to save everyone.
ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Family_Size, fill = Survived))

# Let's do a stacked barchart to evaluated proportion next.
# It shows that yes, people traveling alone Survived poorly, but so did Family_Size of 4 and 5, but we see
# zero Survived for family sizes of 7 and 10 (probably weren't willing to leave family behind).  The best case
# Survival was Family_Size 1,2 and 3 in terms of proportionate odds.
ggplot(data=titanic) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Family_Size, fill = Survived),
           position = "fill")

### now LETS TRY PLOTTING FAMILY_SIZE VS. TITLE AND SURVIVED.  The plot created shows that for a family size of zero 
### singles traveling alone, the majority of them (turquoise) were "Mr", and only a minority were "Mrs", so that confirms 
### that part of the reason people traveling alone died were because they were men, not just because they were alone.
### If you look at the Family_Size (3rd chart) when Family_Size = 0, there are about 550 of those, and approximately 160 
### out of 550 survived, or 29% (ball park).  For the chart below, there are again about 550 with zero Family_Size and about 
### 130 people are Miss or Mrs, so 130/550 = ~ 24%. So that tells you most of the zero family size people that survived are 
### women and single men didn't do well on surviving.
titanic$Family_Size<-as.factor(titanic$Family_Size)
titanic$Title <- as.factor(titanic$Title)
titanic$Survived <- as.character(titanic$Survived)

ggplot(data = titanic, mapping = aes(x = Family_Size, fill = Title)) +
         geom_bar()

MULTI VARIABLE ANALYSIS STATISTICAL LOOK USING DPLYR PIPES AND SUMMARIZE ** PART A **

# REINITIALIZE IN CASE YOU RUN THIS BLOCK OUT OF ORDER
library(tidyverse)
library(readxl)
library(stringr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(knitr)

titanic <- read_xlsx('titanic_partial.xlsx')
#titanic$Pclass <- as.character(titanic$Pclass)
#titanic$Survived <- as.factor(titanic$Survived)

#titanic$Title <- as.character(titanic$Title)

# NOW LET'S USE THE %>% PIPES/FILTERING PLUS SUMMARISE TO LOOK AT JUST DATA TABLES FOR MULTI VARIABLES
# The first one below is from Lesson 138 lines 117-119.  It creates percent_survived 39x5 table with 
# the 5th column being the percent that survived.  If we examine that table, it clearly shows that for
# those variables, Sex is the most significant factor, followed by Pclass, then family size, so that females with large
# family sizes didn't do as well, but females in Pclass 1 with family sizes 1,2,4,5 all 100% survived.  Females in Pclass 
# 2 and family size 3,4,5 all lived too.  Only then did males in Pclass 1 family size 3 all survive. 9 more female combin-
# ations of Pclass and Family_Size then varied from 97% to 50% before we got to the next male entry at Pclass =2, Family_Size
# = 2 where 47% of 17 survived.  So CLEARLY THE #1 FACTOR FOR SURVIVAL IS SEX.  However, it is notable that there were zero 
# female survivors for Pclass 3, Family_Size 4,5,7,10, even though that totaled 19 females.  

percent_survived <- titanic %>% 
  group_by(Sex, Pclass, Family_Size) %>% 
  summarise(count = n(), avg = mean(Survived, rm.na = TRUE))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Sex', 'Pclass'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
percent_survive_sort <- percent_survived %>% as.data.frame() %>% arrange(desc(avg))

  facet_grid(Cabin_deck ~ Survived)

Summary

Each section is summarized within that section for that table or graph. But to give an overall summary of the results, the primary factor that dictated who survived was Gender/Sex, with women surviving much more than men. After that the second factor was Pclass, with Pclass 1 surviving better than Pclass 2 and much better than Pclass 3. Within gender, trends were explored to see if young/unmarried ladies (Miss) were saved more than married women (Mrs), with somemixed results. The same question was asked about young/unmarried men (Master) vs. married men (Mr). None of the pastors (Rev) survived, and only 3 of 7 doctors (Dr) survived (one because she was female, plus half the Pclass 1 male doctors), so that doesn’t say much about the status of Reverends and Doctors on the ship.

For the factor Age, it was true that older men/women were more often in Pclass 1 and younger men/women were more often in Pclass 3, age was shown not to be a significant factor by a box plot chart, which showed the survivors to have a slightly younger average age (23) than the non-survivors (25), but the plots were very similar, so that isn’t a primary factor.

Disclaimer: Any analysis of Cabin_deck is limited, because only 204 of 891 entries had a Cabin listed. The location of the deck (the letter before the number on the Cabin) was summarized as a 15th column, Cabin_deck. There were some differences seen in the number of people saved from various decks, so some might have been further away from the damage to the ship, or closer to the lifeboats. The Cabin_decks that survived the best were B,D and E, with poorer results from Cabin_decks A, C and G, and no survivors in the small U category. Looking at a Titanic website, the decks were arranged with A at the top, then B,C,D,E,F,G going down towards the hull of the ship. Each deck extended the length of the ship. Pclass 1 was in Decks A,B,C,D,E, and Pclass 2 was in Decks D,E,F. Pclass 3 was held in E,F,G and those decks flooded first. Also, Pclass 3 passengers were required to be kept separate from Pclass 1 and 2 passengers to prevent the spread of disease, and they even were to disembark at a different location at their destination. So as the ship started sinking, staff closed doors, denying Pclass 3 passengers a route to the ship’s surface, which explains why even many women in Pclass 3 died.

The Embarked location (C,Q or S) shows 3x the number of people embarked at location S, but it had the poorest survival rate. Location C had the best survival, but a closer look at embarkation location as a function of Pclass shows that probably the reason location C had the best survival was that it had the largest percentage of Pclass 1 passengers. It was surprising though that location Q was nearly all Pclass 3 passengers but it had the 2nd best survival rate. That is probably due to location S having > 600 passengers, compared to locations C and Q having less than 200 and 100, respectively. It just isn’t easy to save all 600 of the location S people.

The variable Fare was looked at, but really was a proxy for Pclass. The fares were bucketed into groups to plot a cleaner bar chart. It does show a pretty consistent trend of improving Survival as a function of Fare increasing, to no surprise, which matches the Pclass trends.

Next the six titles (Master, Mr, Miss, Mrs, Dr, Rev) were examined for frequency and Survived. The largest group were Mr at 525, followed by Miss at 185, followed by Mrs at 128, Master at 40 and 7 Dr and 6 Rev. Using a stacked barchart, the highest percent Survived was Mrs (above 75%), followed by Miss at about 70% (a net of 74.2% for females); then Master a little above 50%; and Mr at well below 20% (for a net of 18.9% for men). Three of the 7 Dr’s survived and none of the Rev survived.

Next Family_Size (the sum of Parch and SibSp) was examined, along with those two additive components. The largest group was passengers traveling alone, and they had a poor survival rate at about 30%. The best family sizes for Survival were size 3, then 2 then 1. Larger sized families of 4,5,6 did poorly and very large families of 7 and 10 had no survivors, which could probably be expected by families not being willing to leave loved ones behind. But the family size was also cross checked against title, and it was found that the majority of passengers traveling alone were Mr, so that correlates with why most of them couldn’t board life boats - they were men, not just that they were traveling alone. It appears that the percent of survivors in the traveling alone group that were women correlates with the overall percent that survived.

A stacked bar chart was used to look at Pclass, and it confirms that the percent Survival is tied to Pclass 1 being best at about 60% and Pclass 3 being worst at about 25%. So Pclass/Fare/Wealth clearly tied to survival, but only after gender. Gender plots show about 74% of women survived and about 19% of men survived.

After Pclass, Sex was looked at. A standard barchart shows a little about 310 women and about 580 men. Even a quick look this chart shows about 75% of the women survived, and only about 20% of the men survived. A stacked barchart showing the Surviving proportion is also given, which confirms these numbers. Gender is the #1 pareto for who Survived. The History Channel website says the “law of the sea” is that women and children must board the boats first.

Part A of the multivariable analysis created a table called percent_survived (39 obs x 5 variables). A detailed analysis is given in that section, but for example, females in Pclass 1 with family sizes 1,2,4,5 all 100% survived, as did females in Pclass 2 and family size 3,4,5. In contrast, there were zero female survivors for Pclass 3, Family_size 4,5,7,10, even though that was 19 females. Of the men that survived, Pclass 1 with family size 3 all survived, but after that, men did no better than a 50% survival rate. To illustrate that, the next most favorable category for men was Pclass 2, Family_Size 2, where only 47% of 17 men survived. Clearly the #1 Survival factor is sex/gender.

Part B of the multivariable analysis created a table called percent_survived_bydeck (21 obs x 5 variables). This used the earlier Cabin_deck sort. Females in Pclass 1 survived 100% of the time on Cabin_deck A,B,D and E. The females all survived also in Pclass 2 for Cabin_deck D and F. For males, two in Pclass 3 survived 100% on deck E, followed by 4 in Pclass 2 at 75% on Deck F. There is a more detailed analysis in that section, but clearly the people loading the lifeboats were going by gender first and Pclass/Fare/Wealth second, not what Cabin_deck passengers were on.

Part C of the multivariable analysis used a facet grid to create six tables. Each table had Age as the x variable, Fare as the y variable, and was sorted by Survived on the vertical sort, and by Pclass on the horizontal sort. These charts show that only a few females in Pclass 1 and 2 didn’t survive, but we do see in Pclass 3 there were more women that didn’t live, although their number is still small compared to the number of men in Pclass 3 that didn’t survive. There is a slight trend where Pclass 1 tends to be older men/women and Pclass 3 tends to be younger men/women, which is to be expected in terms of wealth vs. age. No correlation is seen in looking at the original Survive/No Survive as a function of age in these six charts, which correlates with the finding from the single-variable analysis that age isn’t a primary factor.

Part D of the multivariable analysis creates a table called percent_survived_bytitle (16 obs x 5 var). This was to see if among ladies, Miss or Mrs survived better, and amoung men if Master or Mr survived better. The surprise here was that there were 12 Masters from Pclass 1 and 2 that did survive just as well as the women. Among the females in Pclass 1, Mrs survived better than Miss by a very small margin but in Pclass 2 it reversed, also by a small margin, all above 90%. But once it got to Pclass 3, the survival rates for women were tied at 50% for both Miss and Mrs. It was notable that once it got down to Pclass 3, there were 28 Masters that survived at 39%, compared to 319 Mr. who survived at 11%, so both in the high and low classes, there did seem to be a preference for the young/unmarried men. It’s possible they were crew who were running the lifeboats or some other tangible reason for that.
